é}}, {{tt|vi|đứa trẻ}}\n* Welsh: {{tt|cy|plentyn dan oed}}\n* Yiddish: {{tt|yi|קינד}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|ọmọdé}}\n* Yucatec Maya: {{t|yua|paal}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt+|zza|qeç}}, {{t+|zza|doman}}\n* Zhuang: {{tt|za|lwgnyez}}\n* Zulu: {{tt+|zu|umntwana|c1|c2}}, {{tt+|zu|ingane|c9|c10}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|(''figuratively'') things or abstractions derived from or caused by something}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|member of a tribe, a people or a race of beings}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|övlad}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|бала|}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|בן|m|tr=ben}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n{{trans-top|(''computing'') object which has a subservient or derivative role relative to another object}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t+|yue|仔|tr=zai2}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|dcera|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|kind|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|lapsiobjekti}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|შვილობილი}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|απότοκος|m}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|barn}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|子|tr=こ, ko}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|barn|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|filho|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|доче́рний}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|mwana}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|barn}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|con}} {{qualifier|only attributively}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|(''mathematics'') subordinate node}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|ido}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Breton: {{t+check|br|krouadur|m}}, {{qualifier|young child}} {{t+check|br|-ien}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{t-check|gug|mitã'i}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+check|id|anak}}, {{t+check|id|bocah}}\n* Interlingua: {{t+check|ia|infante}}\n* Korean: {{t+check|ko|어린이|}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+check|kmr|zarrok}}\n* Maltese: {{t-check|mt|iben}}, {{t+check|mt|tifel}}\n* Persian: {{t+check|fa|بَچِّه|tr=bačče}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|en|orling}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|childen}}, from the noun {{m|enm|child}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|archaic|ambitransitive}} To [[give birth]]; to [[beget]] or [[procreate]].\n#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|year=1596.2|book=VI|canto=XII|stanza=17|page=512|passage= My liefe (ſayd ſhe) ye know, that long ygo, <br> Whileſt ye in durance dwelt, ye to me gaue <br> A little mayde, the which ye '''chylded''' tho&nbsp;; <br> The ſame againe if now ye liſt to haue, <br> The ſame is yonder Lady, whom high God did ſaue.}}\n#* {{RQ:Tasso Fairfax Godfrey of Bulloigne|18|stanza=26|320|And from his fertill hollow wombe forth ran, <br> (Clad in rare weedes and ſtrange habiliment) <br> A Nymph, for age able to goe to man, <br> An hundreth plants beſide (euen in his ſight) <br> '''Childed''' an hundreth Nymphes, ſo great, ſo dight:{{...}}}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare King Lear Q1|act=III|scene=v|passage={{...}}But then the mind much ſufferance doth or'e ſcip, <br> When griefe hath mates,&ZeroWidthSpace;and bearing fellowſhip&nbsp;: <br> How light and portable my paine ſeemes now, <br> When that which makes me bend, makes the King bow, <br> He '''childed''' as I fathered,&ZeroWidthSpace;''Tom'' away, <br> Marke the high noyſes and thy ſelfe bewray,{{...}}}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-see|to give birth|give birth}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* ''[http://m-w.com/dictionary/child Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary]'' (accessed November 2007).\n* ''[http://www.thefreedictionary.com/child American Heritage Dictionary]'', Fourth Edition, Houghton Mifflin Company (2003).\n\n{{cln|en|nouns with irregular plurals}}\n{{C|en|Age|Children|Family members|People}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|enm|chelde|childe|chyld|chylde|cild}}\n* {{alter|enm|cild||early}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|enm|ang|ċild}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*kelþaz}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|enm|/t͡ʃiːld/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{enm-noun|pl=children|pl2=childre|pl3=childres|pl4=child|pl3_qual=rare|pl4_qual=early}}\n\n# A {{l|en|child}}, {{gloss|[[person]] who has [[not]] [[reach]]ed [[adulthood]]}}:\n## A [[baby]], [[infant]], [[toddler]]; a person in [[infancy]].\n## {{lb|enm|Christianity}} The [[Christ child]]; [[Jesus]] as a {{l|en|child}}.\n# A young [[male]], especially a [[hireling]] or [[squire]].\n# The young of [[animals]] or [[plants]].\n# An [[offspring]], one of one's [[progeny]].\n# A [[childish]] or [[stupid]] [[individual]].\n# {{lb|enm|figurative}} A [[follower]] of a [[religion]] {{q|usually with the religion in the genitive preposing it}}\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} A [[result]] or [[product]].\n\n====Declension====\n{{enm-decl-noun|child|childes|childe|[[childre]], [[children]]|[[childres]], [[childrene]]}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col4|enm|\n|child bed\n|childberyng\n|childen\n|Childermasse day\n|childhode\n|childing\n|childissh\n|childles\n|childly\n|childwyte\n|knave child\n|mayde child\n|mayden child\n|stepchild\n}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|en|child}}\n* {{desc|sco|child}}; {{l|sco|chield}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=chīld|pos=n|id=MED7559 |accessdate=2018-04-23}}\n\n{{C|enm|Babies|Children|Family|Nobility|People}}\n{{cln|enm|z-stem nouns}}"}}